('genetics_colours', 'easy', 'What are the AKC standard-accepted French Bulldog coat colours?', 'Fawn, brindle, white, cream, and combinations of these', 'Any colour including blue and merle', 'Only fawn and white', 'Black, brown, and white', 'The AKC breed standard accepts all brindle, fawn, white, brindle and white, and any combination except disqualifying colours.', 'The original 1897 standard only accepted brindle. Fawn, cream, and piebald were added in 1911.', 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'easy', 'What term describes a French Bulldog with a mostly white coat with coloured patches?', 'Pied (piebald)', 'Merle', 'Tuxedo', 'Spotted', 'Pied Frenchies have a predominantly white coat with patches of another colour, typically brindle or fawn.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'easy', 'What pattern gives French Bulldogs a "tiger stripe" appearance?', 'Brindle', 'Merle', 'Sable', 'Ticked', 'Brindle creates a pattern of dark stripes on a fawn background, ranging from sparse stripes to heavy concentration that appears almost black.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'easy', 'Is the blue (grey) coat colour accepted by the AKC for French Bulldogs?', 'No, it is a disqualifying colour', 'Yes, it is standard', 'Yes, but only for females', 'Only in combination with white', 'The AKC standard lists "mouse" (blue/grey) as a disqualifying colour. Blue Frenchies cannot compete in conformation shows.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'easy', 'What is the most common French Bulldog coat pattern?', 'Brindle', 'Solid fawn', 'Pied', 'Cream', 'Brindle is one of the most common colours/patterns seen in French Bulldogs.', NULL, 0, 1),

('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What two genes must both be homozygous recessive to produce a lilac French Bulldog?', 'Blue dilution (d/d) and chocolate (b/b)', 'Blue dilution (d/d) and cream (e/e)', 'Chocolate (b/b) and brindle (Kbr)', 'Cream (e/e) and fawn (Ay)', 'Lilac requires both copies of the dilution gene (d/d) and both copies of the chocolate gene (b/b), creating a distinctive pale purple-grey colour.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What genetic locus controls the brindle pattern in French Bulldogs?', 'K locus (dominant black/brindle)', 'A locus (agouti)', 'D locus (dilution)', 'E locus (extension)', 'The K locus controls brindle expression. The Kbr allele produces the brindle striping pattern over the base colour.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What causes the "cream" colour in French Bulldogs?', 'Two copies of the recessive e allele (e/e) at the E locus', 'A dilution of black pigment', 'Two copies of the white gene', 'A mixture of fawn and white genes', 'Cream is caused by the homozygous recessive e/e genotype at the E locus, which prevents the production of dark (eumelanin) pigment in the coat.', 'The cream gene also masks (deletes) any black mask the dog might carry.', 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What is the AKC term for the blue/grey colour in French Bulldogs?', 'Mouse', 'Slate', 'Silver', 'Steel', 'The AKC standard uses the term "mouse" to describe the blue-grey colour produced by the dilution gene. It is a disqualifying colour.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What creates the melanistic mask (black face mask) on fawn French Bulldogs?', 'The Em allele at the E locus', 'The A locus agouti gene', 'The K locus brindle gene', 'The D locus dilution gene', 'The melanistic mask is controlled by the Em allele at the E locus. Only one copy is needed for the mask to appear.', 'The cream gene (e/e) will erase the mask if the dog carries two copies.', 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What is a "reverse brindle" French Bulldog?', 'A brindle where fawn stripes predominate on a dark background', 'A brindle that runs backwards', 'A brindle without any stripes', 'A brindle that changes colour seasonally', 'Light or "tiger" brindle where the lighter fawn colour is more visible is sometimes called reverse brindle. It is generally more rare.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What makes a "sable" French Bulldog different from a standard fawn?', 'Sable Frenchies have darker to black-tipped hairs overlaying a fawn base', 'Sable Frenchies have spots instead of solid colour', 'Sable is just another name for dark fawn', 'Sable Frenchies have curly fur', 'Sable occurs when a Fawn Frenchie has a thin layer of darker to black-tipped hairs on top of the fawn coat, controlled by the Ay/At combination at the A locus.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What is "ticking" in French Bulldog coat patterns?', 'Small flecked spots on white areas of the coat', 'Large patches of colour', 'Stripes on the legs only', 'Colour that changes with age', 'Ticking refers to small freckle-like spots on the white portions of a pied coat. It is accepted by the AKC but not desired.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What colours are listed as disqualifications in the AKC French Bulldog standard?', 'Solid black, mouse, liver, black and tan, black and white, white with black', 'Only blue and merle', 'Only black and liver', 'All non-fawn colours', 'The standard specifically disqualifies solid black, mouse (blue), liver, black and tan, black and white, and white with black.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What is the difference between a "black" and a "black brindle" French Bulldog?', 'Black brindle has a trace of brindle pattern; solid black has no brindle at all', 'There is no difference', 'Black brindle is lighter', 'Black is accepted and black brindle is not', 'The AKC specifies "black means black without a trace of brindle." A dark dog with even minimal brindle striping is a black brindle, which is acceptable. Solid black is a disqualification.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'medium', 'What genetic locus is responsible for the piebald (pied) pattern?', 'S locus (spotting gene)', 'K locus', 'A locus', 'M locus', 'The S locus controls white spotting patterns. Two copies of the s allele (s/s) typically produce the pied pattern.', NULL, 0, 1),

('genetics_colours', 'hard', 'What gene and locus is responsible for the merle pattern in dogs?', 'PMEL17 gene at the M locus', 'TYRP1 gene at the B locus', 'MLPH gene at the D locus', 'MC1R gene at the E locus', 'The merle pattern is caused by a mutation in the PMEL17 (SILV) gene at the M locus, creating patches of diluted colour.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'hard', 'What is an "Isabella" French Bulldog?', 'A double dilute carrying both blue (d/d) and testable chocolate (b/b)', 'A very light cream Frenchie', 'A red fawn with no mask', 'A brindle with unusual striping', 'Isabella, also known as "true lilac" or double dilute, requires two copies each of both the blue and testable chocolate genes.', 'Isabella Frenchies typically have milky brown coats and green or amber eyes.', 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'hard', 'What does "New Shade Isabella" mean in French Bulldog genetics?', 'A dog carrying d/d, b/b, and co/co (triple dilute)', 'A lighter version of standard Isabella', 'An Isabella with a black mask', 'An Isabella born from two standard parents', 'New Shade Isabella carries two copies each of blue (d/d), testable chocolate (b/b), and cocoa (co/co), creating a distinctive goldish-brown coat.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'hard', 'What A locus genotype produces tan points (tricolour) in French Bulldogs?', 'At/At or At/a', 'Ay/Ay', 'a/a', 'Aw/Aw', 'The At allele at the A locus produces the tan point pattern. Dogs that are At/At or At/a express tan points on legs, chest, cheeks, and eyebrows.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'hard', 'What is the "L gene" responsible for in French Bulldogs?', 'Long hair (fluffy coat)', 'Liver colouring', 'Large size', 'Light eyes', 'The L gene controls coat length. Two copies of the recessive l allele produce long-haired "fluffy" French Bulldogs.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'hard', 'What A locus genotype produces a solid non-brindle black French Bulldog?', 'a/a (recessive black)', 'At/At', 'Ay/Ay', 'Aw/Aw', 'Solid black (without brindle) is produced by the homozygous recessive a/a genotype at the A locus, combined with no brindle at the K locus.', NULL, 0, 1),
('genetics_colours', 'hard', 'Why can the merle pattern sometimes be "hidden" or invisible on a French Bulldog?', 'Other coat colours and patterns can mask the merle dilution effect', 'Merle fades as the dog ages', 'Merle only appears in sunlight', 'Merle is always visible', 'The merle coat pattern can hide under other colours, which is why genetic testing is critical before breeding to avoid accidental double merle matings.', NULL, 0, 1),

